The paper deals with computational topology and algorithms for computing homology classes, which are relevant to several subfields of computer science. The use of persistent homology and finite field algebra suggests a connection to computational geometry (cs.CG) and numerical analysis (cs.NA). The focus on measuring and localizing homology classes may also be relevant to data mining (cs.DM) and machine learning (cs.LG), as well as to applications in sensor networks and distributed computing (cs.SI). Finally, the use of algorithms and complexity analysis suggests a connection to data structures (cs.DS).
